Abstract

Welcome to my final project report for DAT 494 Deep learning class.

In this project, I have implemented a multiclass CNN classifier model that can classify different traffic signs on the road, a fundamental task in broader context of autonomous driving. I selected this topic because I want to explore about how self driving cars perceive and recognize objects in real time. Through this project, I have experimented on data manupulations techniques using pandas, implementing CNNs models, achieving best accuracy by following different optimization techniques. I am able to get 99.46% accuracy on validation set. I saved the best performing model (minimum validation loss), and got 96.38% accuracy on test set.

In[11]:
'''
Custom dataset loader to get images, and corresponding ClassId(labels).
returns image(as tensor after transforms), label, which will be used by DataLoader
'''
class TrafficSignDataset(Dataset):
  # stores dataframe, root directory, transforms (pass diffent data and transforms- train, test)
  def __init__(self, dataframe, image_dir, transforms=None):
    self.dataframe = dataframe.reset_index(drop=True)
    self.image_dir = image_dir
    self.transforms = transforms

  # get length of the dataframe -> required by DataLoader (iteration)
  def __len__(self):
    return len(self.dataframe)

  # get images from folder and classId. if transforms given, apply transforms (data augmentation for train_transforms)
  def __getitem__(self, index):
    image_path = os.path.join(self.image_dir, self.dataframe.loc[index, 'Path'])
    image = Image.open(image_path)
    label = self.dataframe.loc[index, 'ClassId']

    if self.transforms:
      image = self.transforms(image)

    return image, label

Transforms and data loaders

Here, I define two transforms: one for train dataset and another for validation and test datasets.

First, I resize the images to dim=32x32 The train_transform will have data augmentation: RandomHorizontalFlip(), RandomRotation(), ColorJitter(). This helps the model to give a generalized performance and hence, helps in predicting unseen data. Added Normalization with mean and standard deviation values used by ImageNet for RGB.

In[12]:
# Defining transforms with data augmentation, and defining train loader, validation loader, test loader

train_transform = transforms.Compose([
    # Resizing images to 32x32 for easier computation and uniform size for cnn layers
    transforms.Resize((32, 32)),

    # Randomly do horizontal flip, with probability default- 0.5 (50%)
    transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),

    # rotate 15 degress on random image
    transforms.RandomRotation(15),

    # change brightness, saturation, contrast, hue of image
    transforms.ColorJitter(brightness=0.2, contrast=0.2, saturation=0.2, hue=0.1),
    transforms.ToTensor(),

    # Referred to imageNet mean and standard deviation for RGB
    transforms.Normalize((0.485, 0.456, 0.406), (0.229, 0.224, 0.225))
])

# Defining a separate transform for validation and test datasets (here, data augmentation for generalization is not necessary)

val_test_transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((32, 32)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
    transforms.Normalize((0.485, 0.456, 0.406), (0.229, 0.224, 0.225))
])

# Creating 3 datasets; giving dataframe, path to files(colab directory), transform to TrafficSignDataset class
train_dataset = TrafficSignDataset(train_data, '/content/gtsrb-german-traffic-sign/', transforms=train_transform)
val_dataset = TrafficSignDataset(val_data, '/content/gtsrb-german-traffic-sign/', transforms=val_test_transform)
test_dataset = TrafficSignDataset(test_df, '/content/gtsrb-german-traffic-sign/', transforms=val_test_transform)

# Dataloaders: wraps iterable around the dataset to enable easy access to the samples (Pytorch documentation)
train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=32, shuffle=True) # randomize order
val_loader = DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=32, shuffle=False)
test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=32, shuffle=False)

Model Architecture

Inspired from VGG architecture, I have implemented a simpler version: 3 blocks of conv2d layers with 2 convolution layers in one block. 1 fully connected layer, and 1 output layer that has 43 neurons (for 43 classes).

Included BatchNormalization after each convolution layer to prevent overfitting, improves regularization, and faster convergence. Dropout added between two blocks to prevent overfitting.

In[14]:
# Model definition Following VGG architecture: 2x conv layer followed by maxPool between the blocks. Simple VGG, that can extract necessary features.
# BatchNormalization after each conv2d layer - for early convergence, faster and stable learning.
# Dropout - randomly sets fraction of units to zeros (eg. 25% of activation are set to zero) - regularization technique
class TrafficSignModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(TrafficSignModel, self).__init__()

        # block 1
        self.conv1_1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn1_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(32)
        self.conv1_2 = nn.Conv2d(32, 32, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn1_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(32)
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout1 = nn.Dropout(0.25)

        # block 2
        self.conv2_1 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn2_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.conv2_2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn2_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout2 = nn.Dropout(0.25)

        # block 3
        self.conv3_1 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn3_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(128)
        self.conv3_2 = nn.Conv2d(128, 128, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding='same')
        self.bn3_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(128)
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        self.dropout3 = nn.Dropout(0.25)

        self.flatten = nn.Flatten()

        # fully connected layer and output layer
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(128 * 4 * 4, 512)
        self.bn4 = nn.BatchNorm1d(512)
        self.dropout4 = nn.Dropout(0.5)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(512, 43)

    # Using nn.Functional - stateless functions that does operations(Here, activations)
    def forward(self, x):
        # block 1
        x = F.relu(self.bn1_1(self.conv1_1(x)))
        x = F.relu(self.bn1_2(self.conv1_2(x)))
        x = self.pool1(x)
        x = self.dropout1(x)

        # block 2
        x = F.relu(self.bn2_1(self.conv2_1(x)))
        x = F.relu(self.bn2_2(self.conv2_2(x)))
        x = self.pool2(x)
        x = self.dropout2(x)

        # block 3
        x = F.relu(self.bn3_1(self.conv3_1(x)))
        x = F.relu(self.bn3_2(self.conv3_2(x)))
        x = self.pool3(x)
        x = self.dropout3(x)

        # flatten before introducing to fc layers
        x = self.flatten(x)
        #print(x.shape)

        # fully connected layers
        x = F.relu(self.bn4(self.fc1(x)))
        x = self.dropout4(x)
        x = self.fc2(x)

        return x
In[15]:
# training loop
num_epochs = 15

# setting this to update best model with respect to best validation loss
best_val_loss = float('inf')

# running using GPU if available
device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
model = TrafficSignModel().to(device)

# loss function -> internally applies softmax
loss_function = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

#optimizer: Used Adam(momentum+RMSProp), adaptive learning rate, faster convergence) optimizer with weight_decay (adding penalty), generalizated performance and prevent overfitting
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.001, weight_decay=1e-4)

# log history for plotting loss and accuracy graphs
train_losses = []
train_accuracies = []
val_losses = []
val_accuracies = []

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
  #ensure model is in train mode
  model.train()
  total_loss = 0.0

  # for accuracy
  correct = 0
  total = 0

  for images, labels in train_loader:
    images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)

    # get prediction
    results = model(images)

    # loss:
    loss = loss_function(results, labels)

    # backpropagation steps
    optimizer.zero_grad() # clear gradients accumulated in previous batches by backward call
    loss.backward() # calculates gradient (dL/dP)
    optimizer.step() # updates parameters to reduce loss

    # total loss
    total_loss += loss.item()
    i, predicted = torch.max(results.data, 1)
    total += labels.size(0)
    correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

  # Get train accuracy and train loss
  train_loss = total_loss/len(train_loader)
  train_accuracy = 100 * correct/total

  ## validation set, ensure model is set to eval
  model.eval()
  val_loss = 0.0
  val_correct = 0
  val_total = 0

  with torch.no_grad():
    for images, labels in val_loader:
      images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
      results = model(images)
      loss = criterion(results, labels)
      val_loss += loss.item()
      i, predicted = torch.max(results.data, 1)
      val_total += labels.size(0)
      val_correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

  # Get loss and accuracy
  val_loss = val_loss/len(val_loader)
  val_accuracy = 100 * val_correct/val_total

  # update values for each epoch and print them
  print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs}, Training Loss: {train_loss:.4f}, Training Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.2f}, Validation Loss: {val_loss:.4f}, Validation Accuracy: {val_accuracy:.2f}%")

  # get loss and accuracy history for train and validation sets
  train_losses.append(train_loss)
  train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)
  val_losses.append(val_loss)
  val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

  # if new validation loss is less than existing best model, model is updated and saved as best model.
  if val_loss < best_val_loss:
    best_val_loss = val_loss
    torch.save(model.state_dict(), 'best_model.pth')
    print(f"Model saved with validation loss {best_val_loss:.4f}")

The model performs well with testing dataset as well, giving 96.38% accuracy, little less compared to Validation accuracy. Test loss = 0.1131, more than validation loss of 0.0162. This might be because I save the model that performs best according to validation set.

In[17]:
# Test dataset evaluation

# resetting model
model = TrafficSignModel()
model.load_state_dict(torch.load('best_model.pth'))
model.to(device)

model.eval()

test_loss = 0.0
correct = 0
test_total = 0
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

with torch.no_grad():
  for inputs, labels in test_loader:
    inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
    test_results = model(inputs)
    loss = criterion(test_results, labels)
    test_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)

    _, predicts = torch.max(test_results, 1)
    correct += (predicts == labels).sum().item()
    test_total += labels.size(0)

# Get loss and accuracy
avg_test_loss = test_loss / test_total
test_accuracy = 100 * correct / test_total
print(f"Test Loss: {avg_test_loss:.4f}, Test Accuracy: {test_accuracy:.2f}%")

Test Loss: 0.1131, Test Accuracy: 96.38%
In[24]:
'''
Here, I take a random batch of testing and training images, and use the model to predict and plot the output
denormalizing the images before plotting them, so that it would be clean in the output
Normalized image = (image - mean)/std
Therefore, denormalized image = (normalized image * std) + mean
'''
def deNormalize(normalized_image, mean, std):
  mean = torch.tensor(mean).view(3,1,1)
  std = torch.tensor(std).view(3,1,1)
  return (normalized_image * std) + mean

# setting the model for evaluation
model.eval()

# Getting from test dataset
images, labels = next(iter(test_loader))
images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)

trainedImages, trainedLabels = next(iter(train_loader))
trainedImages, trainedLabels = trainedImages.to(device), trainedLabels.to(device)

with torch.no_grad():
    outputs_test = model(images)
    outputs_train = model(trainedImages)
    _, y_pred_test = torch.max(outputs_test, 1)
    _, y_pred_train = torch.max(outputs_train, 1)

mean = [0.485, 0.456, 0.406]
std = [0.229, 0.224, 0.225]

print("Testing sets\n")
# Plotting for testing sets
fig, ax = plt.subplots(4, 8, figsize=(12, 6))
ax = ax.flatten()

for i in range(32):
    image = images[i].cpu()
    image = deNormalize(image, mean, std)
    image = image.permute(1, 2, 0).numpy()
    ax[i].imshow(image)
    true_label = labels[i].item()
    pred_label = y_pred_test[i].item()
    color = 'green' if true_label == pred_label else 'red'
    ax[i].set_title(f"T: {true_label}\nP: {pred_label}", fontsize=8, color=color) # T: True label; P: Predicted label
    ax[i].set_axis_off()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


print ("\nTraining sets\n")
# Plotting for training sets
fig, ax = plt.subplots(4, 8, figsize=(12, 6))
ax = ax.flatten()

for i in range(32):
    image = trainedImages[i].cpu()
    image = deNormalize(image, mean, std)
    image = image.permute(1, 2, 0).numpy()
    ax[i].imshow(image)
    true_label = trainedLabels[i].item()
    pred_label = y_pred_train[i].item()
    color = 'green' if true_label == pred_label else 'red'
    ax[i].set_title(f"T: {true_label}\nP: {pred_label}", fontsize=8, color=color) # T: True label; P: Predicted label
    ax[i].set_axis_off()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From the plot that gets a batch of testing and training set, the model is able to correctly predict the label for all of the images but only one in the testing set(label marked red in color). The model performs well for training set batch.
